If these supplementary bones are not prenasalia, another alternative which could explain the condition of
O. leptodon
is the presence of septomaxillae. These bones are present in crossopterygians, lissamphibians, squamates, in all nonmammalian therapsids, and in all the nontherian mammals except multituberculates. The septomaxilla is absent in marsupials and placentals except in Xenarthra ( Wible, 1990 ;
Zeller et al ., 1993
). However, we are reluctant to interpret the supplementary bones of
O. leptodon
as septomaxillae, since the study of the development of the nasal capsule of odontocetes ( Klima & Van Bree, 1985 ;
Klima et al ., 1986
; Klima, 1987 ) does not show any indication that such bones are present at any developmental stage in this group.
